{"type":"message","id":"9960cf36","parentId":"3f461ba5","timestamp":"2026-02-15T12:14:39.329Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Considering Relevant Files**\n\nI've been going through the files, and it seems like `src/agent_wrapper.py` and `docs_archive/MASTER_PROTOCOL.md` are quite important. I'm focusing on the Telegram bot's API interaction, and `DMarket-Telegram-Bot-main/src/dmarket/dmarket_api.py` looks very relevant, compared to a potentially redundant copy.\n\n\n**Beginning Implementation Steps**\n\nI'm now zeroing in on `src/agent_wrapper.py` and strategizing the background thread implementation. Reading the file, my current plan is to add a file monitoring feature, using `docs_archive/MASTER_PROTOCOL.md` to trigger a reload. The Telegram bot integration is still my main goal.\n\n\n"},{"type":"text","text":"I will read the contents of `src/agent_wrapper.py` to understand where to inject the hot reload logic.\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"read_1771157679324_600","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"src/agent_wrapper.py"},"thoughtSignature":""}],"api":"google-vertex","provider":"google-vertex","model":"gemini-3-pro-preview","usage":{"input":6266,"output":252,"cacheRead":5073,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":6518,"cost":{"input":0.012532,"output":0.003024,"cacheRead":0.0010146,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0165706}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1771157673644}}
{"type":"message","id":"1b78b9d9","parentId":"9960cf36","timestamp":"2026-02-15T12:14:39.347Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"read_1771157679324_600","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"import sys\nimport os\nimport subprocess\nimport argparse\nimport signal\nimport time\n\nPID_FILE = \"src/bot.pid\"\nBOT_SCRIPT = \"src/trading_bot.py\"\n\ndef is_running(pid):\n    \"\"\"Check if a process with the given PID is running.\"\"\"\n    try:\n        # Windows-specific check could be added here, but signal 0 is widely supported for existence check\n        # On Windows, os.kill with 0 is not supported in older versions, but usually fine in modern Python.\n        # Alternative: use tasklist\n        if os.name == 'nt':\n            # Use tasklist to check if PID exists\n            # Use errors='ignore' to handle potential non-UTF-8 output from localized Windows shell\n            output = subprocess.check_output(f'tasklist /FI \"PID eq {pid}\"', shell=True).decode(errors='ignore')\n            return str(pid) in output\n        else:\n            os.kill(pid, 0)\n            return True\n    except (OSError, subprocess.CalledProcessError):\n        return False\n\ndef start_bot():\n    if os.path.exists(PID_FILE):\n        with open(PID_FILE, 'r') as f:\n            try:\n                pid = int(f.read().strip())\n                if is_running(pid):\n                    print(f\"Bot is already running (PID: {pid}).\")\n                    return\n                else:\n                    print(\"Found stale PID file. Cleaning up.\")\n            except ValueError:\n                print(\"Invalid PID file. Cleaning up.\")\n        \n        os.remove(PID_FILE)\n\n    print(\"Starting bot...\")\n    # Detached execution\n    if os.name == 'nt':\n        # Windows: specific flags to detach\n        process = subprocess.Popen(\n            [sys.executable, BOT_SCRIPT],\n            creationflags=subprocess.CREATE_NEW_CONSOLE,\n            cwd=os.getcwd()\n        )\n    else:\n        # Unix\n        process = subprocess.Popen(\n            [sys.executable, BOT_SCRIPT],\n            stdout=subprocess.DEVNULL,\n            stderr=subprocess.DEVNULL,\n            stdin=subprocess.DEVNULL,\n            cwd=os.getcwd(),\n            start_new_session=True\n        )\n\n    with open(PID_FILE, 'w') as f:\n        f.write(str(process.pid))\n    \n    print(f\"Bot started with PID: {process.pid}\")\n\ndef stop_bot():\n    if not os.path.exists(PID_FILE):\n        print(\"Bot is not running (no PID file).\")\n        return\n\n    with open(PID_FILE, 'r') as f:\n        try:\n            pid = int(f.read().strip())\n        except ValueError:\n            print(\"Invalid PID file.\")\n            os.remove(PID_FILE)\n            return\n\n    if is_running(pid):\n        print(f\"Stopping bot (PID: {pid})...\")\n        try:\n            if os.name == 'nt':\n                subprocess.call(['taskkill', '/F', '/T', '/PID', str(pid)])\n            else:\n                os.kill(pid, signal.SIGTERM)\n        except Exception as e:\n            print(f\"Error stopping bot: {e}\")\n    else:\n        print(\"Bot process not found. Cleaning up PID file.\")\n\n    if os.path.exists(PID_FILE):\n        os.remove(PID_FILE)\n    print(\"Bot stopped.\")\n\ndef status_bot():\n    if os.path.exists(PID_FILE):\n        with open(PID_FILE, 'r') as f:\n            content = f.read().strip()\n            # print(f\"DEBUG: Read '{content}'\")\n            try:\n                pid = int(content)\n                if is_running(pid):\n                    print(f\"STATUS: ACTIVE (PID: {pid})\")\n                    return\n                else:\n                    print(\"STATUS: INACTIVE (Stale PID file found)\")\n            except Exception as e:\n                print(f\"STATUS: ERROR (Corrupted PID file): {e}\")\n    else:\n        print(\"STATUS: INACTIVE\")\n\ndef main():\n    parser = argparse.ArgumentParser(description=\"Bot Control Interface\")\n    parser.add_argument('command', choices=['/start_bot', '/stop_bot', '/status'], help=\"Command to execute\")\n    \n    if len(sys.argv) < 2:\n        parser.print_help()\n        sys.exit(1)\n\n    args = parser.parse_args()\n\n    if args.command == '/start_bot':\n        start_bot()\n    elif args.command == '/stop_bot':\n        stop_bot()\n    elif args.command == '/status':\n        status_bot()\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    main()\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1771157679345}}
{"type":"message","id":"3d010068","parentId":"1b78b9d9","timestamp":"2026-02-15T12:14:48.809Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Investigating the Wrapper**\n\nI'm now zeroing in on `agent_wrapper.py`. It's just a launcher for the bot, not the bot itself, which makes integrating hot-reload in this file the correct approach. I need to figure out how to best integrate it into the wrapper script for it to take effect.\n\n\n**Clarifying the Approach**\n\nI'm starting to see that `agent_wrapper.py`'s current role is just to launch the bot. The user wants hot-reload of the protocol, but the code implies this function is within the running process. The question is: should `agent_wrapper.py` monitor and restart the bot, or should the bot itself handle the reload? I'll analyze `src/trading_bot.py` to clarify the correct implementation.\n\n\n**Assessing the Implications**\n\nNow, I'm analyzing the implications of modifying `agent_wrapper.py` to continuously monitor the protocol file. This fundamentally changes its role. The user's instructions imply this is the intended solution, however, I am still unsure if `agent_wrapper.py` should watch the file and restart `src/trading_bot.py`, or if `trading_bot.py` should handle the reload itself. The `reload_protocol()` instruction suggests the latter, yet the edit instruction targets the wrapper. I'll need to examine `trading_bot.py` to decide the best path forward.\n\n\n"},{"type":"text","text":"I will read `src/trading_bot.py` to understand its current implementation and determine the best way to integrate the hot reload functionality.\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"read_1771157688802_602","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"src/trading_bot.py"},"thoughtSignature":""}],"api":"google-vertex","provider":"google-vertex","model":"gemini-3-pro-preview","usage":{"input":7584,"output":576,"cacheRead":5397,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":8160,"cost":{"input":0.015168,"output":0.006912,"cacheRead":0.0010794,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0231594}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1771157679347}}
{"type":"message","id":"f11073c6","parentId":"3d010068","timestamp":"2026-02-15T12:14:48.827Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"read_1771157688802_602","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"import time\nimport sys\nimport os\n\ndef main():\n    print(f\"[{time.strftime('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S')}] BOT STARTED. PID: {os.getpid()}\")\n    sys.stdout.flush()\n    try:\n        while True:\n            print(f\"[{time.strftime('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S')}] Bot running... monitoring markets.\")\n            sys.stdout.flush()\n            time.sleep(5)\n    except KeyboardInterrupt:\n        print(f\"[{time.strftime('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S')}] BOT STOPPING...\")\n    except Exception as e:\n        print(f\"[{time.strftime('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S')}] BOT CRASHED: {e}\")\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    main()\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1771157688825}}
{"type":"message","id":"dc066031","parentId":"f11073c6","timestamp":"2026-02-15T12:14:56.849Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Envisioning Persistent Processes**\n\nI'm currently considering how to make `agent_wrapper.py` persistent. The goal is to avoid restarting the entire trading bot for every change. If I can achieve hot-reloading within `agent_wrapper.py`, the trading bot will be the core process and it will loop, so modifications shouldn't require restarts.\n\n\n**Analyzing The Architecture**\n\nI'm now thinking about how to integrate the monitoring task into `agent_wrapper.py`. It seems the user intends for it to become a supervisor process. Adding a background thread for monitoring makes sense in this scenario, especially considering the daemon-like behavior. I'm focusing on making `agent_wrapper.py` the core process responsible for launching and reloading `trading_bot.py`. I'll next examine `MASTER_PROTOCOL.md` to understand the configuration it holds.\n\n\n"},{"type":"text","text":"I will read `docs_archive/MASTER_PROTOCOL.md` to understand the configuration that needs to be reloaded.\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"read_1771157696841_603","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"docs_archive/MASTER_PROTOCOL.md"},"thoughtSignature":""}],"api":"google-vertex","provider":"google-vertex","model":"gemini-3-pro-preview","usage":{"input":8129,"output":432,"cacheRead":5408,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":8561,"cost":{"input":0.016257999999999998,"output":0.005184,"cacheRead":0.0010816,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.022523599999999998}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1771157688827}}
{"type":"message","id":"a47a84cf","parentId":"dc066031","timestamp":"2026-02-15T12:14:56.866Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"read_1771157696841_603","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# MASTER PROTOCOL (Supreme Law)\n\n**Version:** 1.0.0  \n**Status:** ACTIVE  \n**Enforcement:** MANDATORY  \n**Authority:** PRO STREAM\n\n---\n\n## 1. PREAMBLE\nThis Master Protocol serves as the immutable \"Supreme Law\" for the OpenClaw Trading Automation System. All agents, sub-agents, and human operators must adhere to these directives. No code shall be deployed, no trade executed, and no system modified in violation of these tenets.\n\n---\n\n## 2. SACS-2026 (System Availability & Continuity Standard)\n**Objective:** Guarantee 99.99% uptime for core trading loops.\n\n*   **Fleet Integrity:** All 12 core agents (QUANT, NET, SENTINEL, OPS, DB, LOG, DMARKET, STEAM, HYPE, INVENTORY, SEC, LOGIC) must be active.\n*   **Heartbeat Protocol:** Every component must emit a heartbeat every 30 seconds. Three missed heartbeats trigger an automatic restart sequence.\n*   **Redundancy:** Critical paths (Price Feed, Order Execution) must have N+1 failover redundancy.\n\n## 3. ATOMIC ROLLBACK PROTOCOL\n**Objective:** Zero undefined states.\n\n*   **Definition:** Every deployment or configuration change is a transaction.\n*   **The Rule of Two:**\n    1.  **Pre-Flight Snapshot:** No change proceeds without a verified system snapshot.\n    2.  **Verification Gate:** Post-deployment validation must pass 100% of critical tests within 60 seconds.\n*   **Failure Response:** If Verification Gate fails, the system must *automatically* and *atomically* revert to the Pre-Flight Snapshot. No manual intervention required for safety restoration.\n\n## 4. SPEC-FIRST DEVELOPMENT\n**Objective:** Documentation leads implementation.\n\n*   **Workflow:**\n    1.  **Draft:** Create/Update the Markdown specification (e.g., `docs_archive/FEATURE.md`).\n    2.  **Review:** Validate the spec against the Master Protocol.\n    3.  **Code:** Implement strictly according to the approved spec.\n    4.  **Verify:** Tests must trace back to specific lines in the spec.\n*   **Prohibition:** \"Cowboy coding\" (implementation without documentation) is strictly forbidden.\n\n## 5. OBSERVABILITY & METRICS\n**Objective:** Total visibility, zero blind spots.\n\n*   **Logging:** JSON-structured logs are mandatory for all machine-readable events.\n*   **Metrics:**\n    *   **Latency:** Tracking of `tick-to-trade` latency at p50, p99, and p99.9.\n    *   **Error Rate:** Alert threshold at >1% error rate on any API interface.\n    *   **P&L:** Real-time tracking of Profit & Loss per strategy and aggregate.\n*   **Dashboards:** Monitoring states must be accessible via CLI (`/status`) and visual dashboards.\n\n## 6. HFT RULES (High-Frequency Trading)\n**Objective:** Speed with safety.\n\n*   **Risk Limits:**\n    *   **Max Drawdown:** Hard stop at 2% daily drawdown.\n    *   **Position Sizing:** No single position > 5% of total capital.\n    *   **Kill Switch:** A global hardware/software kill switch must be available to terminate all active orders in < 100ms.\n*   **Execution:**\n    *   **Maker/Taker:** Prefer Maker orders to capture rebate/spread unless high-urgency Taker liquidity is required.\n    *   **Inventory:** maintain neutral inventory exposure where possible (delta neutral strategies).\n\n---\n\n## 7. MODEL OPTIMIZATION STRATEGY\n**Objective:** Leverage AI model strengths for specific roles.\n\n### 7.1. Architect/Trader (Gemini 3 Pro)\n*   **Role:** Complex pattern recognition, strategy formulation, market analysis.\n*   **Context:** 1M+ token window for full historical price data analysis.\n*   **Configuration:**\n    *   `Temperature`: 0.7 (Balanced Creativity)\n    *   `Top_P`: 0.95\n*   **Usage:** Weekly strategy reviews, code architecture, anomaly investigation.\n\n### 7.2. Validator/Signal (Gemini 3 Flash)\n*   **Role:** High-speed syntax checking, trade signature validation, safety guardrails.\n*   **Configuration:**\n    *   `Temperature`: 0.0 (Strict Deterministic)\n    *   `Top_P`: 0.1\n*   **Usage:** Pre-trade checks, continuous integration pipelines, log parsing.\n\n---\n*Signed: SYSTEM ORCHESTRATOR*\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1771157696865}}
